dataIdInfo.idPurp:
Users please text carefully:
This is a polygon shapefile. Datum referenced GDA94. Last updated May 2014 at CFA Spatial Information Systems.
There are two ratings reflected in this shapefile (coloured in green & grey in thumbnail): [1] Low Fire Hazard Ratings, synonymous to Low Bushfire Ratings Area (LBRA). [2] Undefined Fire Hazard Ratings are the Metropolitan Fire Districts where CFA has nil involvement for Rating reviews.
Where not identified as being [1] or [2] (i.e. yellow in thumbnail) users may assume High Fire Hazard Ratings, synonymous to High Bushfire Ratings Area (HBRA) for the state of Victoria as discussed by CFA. Note Crown Land, within the yellow in thumbnail, has been rated to be HBRA.
DEPI (Department of Environment & Primary Industry) remains the responsible fire authority for Fire Hazard Ratings for all DEPI jurisdiction. Currently all DEPI land has been assigned HBRA by default. Similarly, MFB remains the responsible fire authority for Fire Hazard Ratings for all MFB jurisdiction. Currently all MFB land has been assiged LBRA by default, except where CFA has overriden to HBRA. You may wish to contact the MFB to confirm their position. Please check ratings with responsible fire authority.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This shapefile is updated and released March 31st on an annual basis, on a rotation of councils.

Currently each council's Fire Hazard Ratings (s.80 The Electricity Safety Act 1998) within CFA jurisdiction is reviewed once every four years.

Where CFA and MFB are within the same municipality, the entire municipality is reviewed by CFA, the Fire Hazard Rating may differ from the MFB default. Users should overlay MFB jurisdiction to view MFB default LBRA.

Where CFA and DEPI are within the same municpality, entire municipality is reviewed by CFA. Users should overlay DEPI jurisdiction to view DEPI default HBRA.

For details refer to http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare/powerline-vegetation-clearance/
